{"cursor":"24685","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist |name = Colin S. Pittendrigh |image = |caption = |birth_date\n= |birth_place = Whatley Bay, England |death_date = |death_place =Bozeman,\nMontana, United States |residence = United States |citizenship = |nationality =\nEnglish |ethnicity = |fields = Chronobiology, Biology |workplaces = |alma_mater\n= University of Durham Princeton University |doctoral_advisor =\n|academic_advisors = |doctoral_students = |notable_students = |known_for =\nCircadian Rhythm |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences =\n|influenced = |awards = |religion = |signature = \n|footnotes = }}\n\n'Colin Pittendrigh' (October 13, 1918 - March 19, 1996) [http://news.stanford.edu/pr/96/960325pittendrig.html] \"Colin\nPittendrigh, 'Father of biological clock,' dies at 77\", March 25, 1996, accessed\nApril 9, 2011. was a US-American biologist of English parentage.\nPittendrigh is regarded as the âfather of the biological clock,â and founded the\nmodern field of chronobiology alongside JÃ¼rgen Aschoff and Erwin BÃ¼nning. He is\nknown for his careful descriptions of the properties of the circadian clock in\nDrosophila and other species, and providing the first formal models of how\ncircadian rhythms entrain (synchronize) to local light-dark cycles.\n\nHe obtained his first degree of botany at University of Durham, and was\nassigned to wartime service as a biologist in Trinidad during World War II\nwhere he studied malaria transmission by mosquitoes. After the war, he attended\nColumbia University to study for his Ph.D. He later joined the faculty of\nPrinceton University and started his chronobiology research.\nHe also co-chaired a Mars exploration project at NASA from 1964 to 1966.\n\nThe defining principle that Pittendrigh developed throughout his career was that\nthe properties of the circadian clock is independent from those of the behaviors\nit controlled. This gave him the freedom of studying the clock through a range\nof physiological functions from Drosophila hatching to rodents locomotor\nactivities. He performed large series of experiments to demonstrate that\ncircadian rhythmicity is intrinsic and independent of environmental cues. He\ncarried out a famous and protracted debate with Frank Brown, of Northwestern\nUniversity, on whether circadian timekeeping is intrinsic or environmentally\ndriven. Pittendrighâs data and argument ultimately prevailed and sparked\ninterest in chronobiology. [http://www.ias.ac.in/resonance/may2006/p14-\n21.pdf] \"Colin Pittendrigh: The Lion in Winter\", RESONANCE May 2006.\n\nPittendrigh died from cancer on Tuesday, March 19, 1996, at his home in Bozeman,\nMontana. He has been regarded as one of the most influential\nfigures in the field, and his research has big influence on the field of\nchronobiology even after he died. The Society for Research on Biological Rhythms\nholds biannual lectures named in honor of Pittendrigh and Aschoff. [http://www.srbr.org/Pages/PittendrighLectures.aspx] \"Society for\nResearch on Biological Rhythms\"\n","linknr":324,"url":"Colin_Pittendrigh","recorded":1376419283,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Colin_Pittendrigh&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Colin_Pittendrigh&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colin_Pittendrigh","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia